==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Treatise
<hw>Trea"tise</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>tretis</ets>, OF. <ets>treitis</ets>, <ets>traitis</ets>, well
made. See <er>Treat</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A written composition
on a particular subject, in which its principles are discussed or
explained; a tract.</def> <rj><au>Chaucer.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>He published a <qex>treatise</qex> in which he maintained that a
marriage between a member of the Church of England and a dissenter was a
nullity.</q> <rj><qau>Macaulay.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A <xex>treatise</xex> implies more form and method than
an <xex>essay</xex>, but may fall short of the fullness and completeness
of a systematic exposition.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>Story; discourse.</def> <mark>[R.]</mark>
<rj><au>Shak.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Treatiser</ent>⟦br⟧
